[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Always pass over *reject* (an absolute file name) even if it is the first found in the search path; in that case, set *variable* using the absolute file name of the *prog-to-check-for* found that is not *reject*.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If *variable* was already set, do nothing.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] The result of this test can be overridden by setting the *variable* variable or the cache variable `ac_cv_prog_*variable*`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Check for each program in the blank-separated list *progs-to-check-for* existing in the *path*.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If one is found, set *variable* to the name of that program.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Otherwise, continue checking the next program in the list.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If none of the programs in the list are found, set *variable* to *value-if-not-found*; if *value-if-not-found* is not specified, the value of *variable* is not changed.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Like `AC_CHECK_PROG`, but first looks for *prog-to-check-for* with a prefix of the target type as determined by `AC_CANONICAL_TARGET`, followed by a dash (see Getting the Canonical System Type).
