[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Like `AC_CHECK_TOOL`, each of the tools in the list *progs-to-check-for* are checked with a prefix of the host type as determined by `AC_CANONICAL_HOST`, followed by a dash (see Getting the Canonical System Type).
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If none of the tools can be found with a prefix, then the first one without a prefix is used.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Like `AC_CHECK_PROG`, but set *variable* to the absolute name of *prog-to-check-for* if found.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] The result of this test can be overridden by setting the *variable* variable.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] A positive result of this test is cached in the `ac_cv_path_*variable*` variable.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Like `AC_CHECK_PROGS`, but if any of *progs-to-check-for* are found, set *variable* to the absolute name of the program found.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If *variable* is not empty, then set the cache variable `ac_cv_path_*variable*` to its value.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Otherwise, check for each program in the blank-separated list *progs-to-check-for* existing in *path*.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] For each program found, execute *feature-test* with `ac_path_*variable*` set to the absolute name of the candidate program.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If no invocation of *feature-test* sets the shell variable `ac_cv_path_*variable*`, then *action-if-not-found* is executed.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] *feature-test* will be run even when `ac_cv_path_*variable*` is set, to provide the ability to choose a better candidate found later in *path*; to accept the current setting and bypass all further checks, *feature-test* can execute `ac_path_*variable*_found=:`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Note that this macro has some subtle differences from `AC_CHECK_PROGS`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] It is designed to be run inside `AC_CACHE_VAL`, therefore, it should have no side effects.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] In particular, *variable* is not set to the final value of `ac_cv_path_*variable*`, nor is `AC_SUBST` automatically run.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Also, on failure, any action can be performed, whereas `AC_CHECK_PROGS` only performs `*variable*=*value-if-not-found*`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Here is an example that searches for an implementation of `m4` that supports the `indir` builtin, even if it goes by the name `gm4` or is not the first implementation on `PATH`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Like `AC_CHECK_TARGET_TOOL`, but set *variable* to the absolute name of the program if it is found.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Like `AC_CHECK_TOOL`, but set *variable* to the absolute name of the program if it is found.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] You might also need to check for the existence of files.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Before using these macros, ask yourself whether a runtime test might not be a better solution.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Be aware that, like most Autoconf macros, they test a feature of the host machine, and therefore, they die when cross-compiling.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Check whether file *file* exists on the native system.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If it is found, execute *action-if-found*, otherwise do *action-if-not-found*, if given.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Cache the result of this test in the `ac_cv_file_*file*` variable, with characters not suitable for a variable name mapped to underscores.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] For each file listed in *files*, execute `AC_CHECK_FILE` and perform either *action-if-found* or *action-if-not-found*.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Like `AC_CHECK_FILE`, this defines ‘HAVE_*file*’ (see Standard Symbols) for each file found and caches the results of each test in the `ac_cv_file_*file*` variable, with characters not suitable for a variable name mapped to underscores.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] The following macros check for the presence of certain C, C++, Fortran, or Go library archive files.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Test whether the library *library* is available by trying to link a test program that calls function *function* with the library.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] *function* should be a function provided by the library.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Use the base name of the library; e.g., to check for -lmp, use ‘mp’ as the *library* argument.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If linking with *library* results in unresolved symbols that would be resolved by linking with additional libraries, give those libraries as the *other-libraries* argument, separated by spaces: e.g., -lXt -lX11.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Otherwise, this macro may fail to detect that *library* is present, because linking the test program can fail with unresolved symbols.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] The *other-libraries* argument should be limited to cases where it is desirable to test for one library in the presence of another that is not already in `LIBS`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] `AC_CHECK_LIB` requires some care in usage, and should be avoided in some common cases.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Many standard functions like `gethostbyname` appear in the standard C library on some hosts, and in special libraries like `nsl` on other hosts.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] On some hosts the special libraries contain variant implementations that you may not want to use.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] These days it is normally better to use `AC_SEARCH_LIBS([gethostbyname], [nsl])` instead of `AC_CHECK_LIB([nsl], [gethostbyname])`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] The result of this test is cached in the `ac_cv_lib_*library*_*function*` variable.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Search for a library defining *function* if it’s not already available.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] This equates to calling ‘AC_LINK_IFELSE([AC_LANG_CALL([], [*function*])])’ first with no libraries, then for each library listed in *search-libs*.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Prepend -l*library* to `LIBS` for the first library found to contain *function*, and run *action-if-found*.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If the function is not found, run *action-if-not-found*.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Otherwise, this macro fails to detect that *function* is present, because linking the test program always fails with unresolved symbols.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] The result of this test is cached in the `ac_cv_search_*function*` variable as ‘none required’ if *function* is already available, as ‘no’ if no library containing *function* was found, otherwise as the -l*library* option that needs to be prepended to `LIBS`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] The following macros check for particular C library functions.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If there is no macro specifically defined to check for a function you need, and you don’t need to check for any special properties of it, then you can use one of the general function-check macros.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Most usual functions can either be missing, or be buggy, or be limited on some architectures.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] This section tries to make an inventory of these portability issues.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] By definition, this list always requires additions.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] A much more complete list is maintained by the Gnulib project (see Gnulib), covering Current POSIX Functions in *Gnulib*, Legacy Functions in *Gnulib*, and Glibc Functions in *Gnulib*.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Please help us keep the Gnulib list as complete as possible.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] On ancient hosts, `exit` returned `int`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] This is because `exit` predates `void`, and there was a long tradition of it returning `int`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] On current hosts, the problem more likely is that `exit` is not declared, due to C++ problems of some sort or another.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] For this reason we suggest that test programs not invoke `exit`, but return from `main` instead.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] The C standard says a successful call `malloc (0)` is implementation dependent.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] It can return either `NULL` or a new non-null pointer.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] The latter is more common (e.g., the GNU C Library) but is by no means universal.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] `AC_FUNC_MALLOC` can be used to insist on non-`NULL` (see Particular Function Checks).
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] POSIX prefers `setenv` to `putenv`; among other things, `putenv` is not required of all POSIX implementations, but `setenv` is.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] POSIX specifies that `putenv` puts the given string directly in `environ`, but some systems make a copy of it instead (e.g., glibc 2.0, or BSD).
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] And when a copy is made, `unsetenv` might not free it, causing a memory leak (e.g., FreeBSD 4).
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] On some systems `putenv ("FOO")` removes ‘FOO’ from the environment, but this is not standard usage and it dumps core on some systems (e.g., AIX).
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] On MinGW, a call `putenv ("FOO=")` removes ‘FOO’ from the environment, rather than inserting it with an empty value.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] It is problematic to call `realloc` with a zero size.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] The C standard says `realloc (NULL, 0)` is equivalent to `malloc (0)`, which means one cannot portably tell whether the call has succeeded if it returns a null pointer.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If `ptr` is non-null, the C standard says `realloc (ptr, 0)` has undefined behavior.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] The `AC_FUNC_REALLOC` macro avoids some of these portability issues.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] In most cases, it is more robust to use `sigaction` when it is available, rather than `signal`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] In C99 and later, if the output array isn’t big enough and if no other errors occur, `snprintf` and `vsnprintf` truncate the output and return the number of bytes that ought to have been produced.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Some older systems, notably Microsoft Windows before Visual Studio 2015 and Windows 10, do not null-terminate the output and return −1 instead.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Portable code can check the return value of `snprintf (buf, sizeof buf, ...)`: if the value is negative or is not less than `sizeof buf`, an error occurred and the contents of `buf` can be ignored.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Alternatively, one of the Gnulib modules related to `snprintf` can be used.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] POSIX specifies that `strerror_r` returns an `int`, but many systems (e.g., the GNU C Library) provide a different version returning a `char *`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] `AC_FUNC_STRERROR_R` can detect which is in use (see Particular Function Checks).
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Android 5.0’s strnlen was broken, because it assumed the addressed array always had at least the specified number of bytes.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] For example, `strnlen ("", SIZE_MAX)` should return 0 but on Android 5.0 it crashed.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] `_SC_PAGESIZE` is standard, but some older systems (e.g., HP-UX 9) have `_SC_PAGE_SIZE` instead.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] The POSIX spec says that `unlink` causes the given file to be removed only after there are no more open file handles for it.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Some non-POSIX hosts have trouble with this requirement, though, and some DOS variants even corrupt the file system.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] On MinGW, `unsetenv` is not available, but a variable ‘FOO’ can be removed with a call `putenv ("FOO=")`, as described under `putenv` above.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] C99 and later provide `va_copy` for copying `va_list` variables.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] It may be available in older environments too, though possibly as `__va_copy` (e.g., `gcc` in strict pre-C99 mode).
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] A fallback to `memcpy (&dst, &src, sizeof (va_list))` gives maximum portability.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] `va_list` is not necessarily just a pointer.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] It can be a `struct`, which means `NULL` is not portable.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Or it can be an array, which means as a function parameter it can be effectively call-by-reference and library routines might modify the value back in the caller.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Normally the C `>>` right shift of a signed type replicates the high bit, giving a so-called “arithmetic” shift.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] But care should be taken since Standard C doesn’t require that behavior.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] On a few platforms (e.g., Cray C by default) zero bits are shifted in, the same as a shift of an unsigned type.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] C divides signed integers by truncating their quotient toward zero, yielding the same result as Fortran.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] However, before C99 the standard allowed C implementations to take the floor or ceiling of the quotient in some cases.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Hardly any implementations took advantage of this freedom, though, and it’s probably not worth worrying about this issue nowadays.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] These macros check for particular C functions—whether they exist, and in some cases how they respond when given certain arguments.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Define `HAVE_ALLOCA_H` if alloca.h defines a working `alloca`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If either method succeeds, define `HAVE_ALLOCA`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Otherwise, set the output variable `ALLOCA` to ‘${LIBOBJDIR}alloca.o’ and define `C_ALLOCA` (so programs can periodically call ‘alloca (0)’ to garbage collect).
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] This variable is separate from `LIBOBJS` so multiple programs can share the value of `ALLOCA` without needing to create an actual library, in case only some of them use the code in `LIBOBJS`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] The ‘${LIBOBJDIR}’ prefix serves the same purpose as in `LIBOBJS` (see `AC_LIBOBJ` vs.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Source files that use `alloca` should start with a piece of code like the following, to declare it properly.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If you don’t want to maintain this piece of code in your package manually, you can instead use the Gnulib module `alloca-opt` or `alloca`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If the `chown` function is available and works (in particular, it should accept -1 for `uid` and `gid`), define `HAVE_CHOWN`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] The result of this macro is cached in the `ac_cv_func_chown_works` variable.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If you want a workaround, that is, a `chown` function that is available and works, you can use the Gnulib module `chown`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If the `closedir` function does not return a meaningful value, define `CLOSEDIR_VOID`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Otherwise, callers ought to check its return value for an error indicator.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Currently this test is implemented by running a test program.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] When cross compiling the pessimistic assumption that `closedir` does not return a meaningful value is made.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] The result of this macro is cached in the `ac_cv_func_closedir_void` variable.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] This macro is obsolescent, as `closedir` returns a meaningful value on current systems.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If the `error_at_line` function is not found, require an `AC_LIBOBJ` replacement of ‘error’.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] The result of this macro is cached in the `ac_cv_lib_error_at_line` variable.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] The `AC_FUNC_ERROR_AT_LINE` macro is obsolescent.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] New programs should use Gnulib’s `error` module.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If the `fnmatch` function conforms to POSIX, define `HAVE_FNMATCH`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Unlike the other specific `AC_FUNC` macros, `AC_FUNC_FNMATCH` does not replace a broken/missing `fnmatch`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] The result of this macro is cached in the `ac_cv_func_fnmatch_works` variable.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] New programs should use Gnulib’s `fnmatch-posix` module.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Behave like `AC_REPLACE_FNMATCH` (*replace*) but also test whether `fnmatch` supports GNU extensions.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Detect common implementation bugs, for example, the bugs in the GNU C Library 2.1.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] The result of this macro is cached in the `ac_cv_func_fnmatch_gnu` variable.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] New programs should use Gnulib’s `fnmatch-gnu` module.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] This macro checks for the `fork` and `vfork` functions.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If a working `fork` is found, define `HAVE_WORKING_FORK`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] This macro checks whether `fork` is just a stub by trying to run it.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If vfork.h is found, define `HAVE_VFORK_H`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If a working `vfork` is found, define `HAVE_WORKING_VFORK`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Otherwise, define `vfork` to be `fork` for backward compatibility with previous versions of `autoconf`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] This macro checks for several known errors in implementations of `vfork` and considers the system to not have a working `vfork` if it detects any of them.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] The results of this macro are cached in the `ac_cv_func_fork_works` and `ac_cv_func_vfork_works` variables.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] In order to override the test, you also need to set the `ac_cv_func_fork` and `ac_cv_func_vfork` variables.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If the `fseeko` and `ftello` functions are available, define `HAVE_FSEEKO`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Define `_LARGEFILE_SOURCE` if necessary to make the prototype visible.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Configure scripts that use `AC_FUNC_FSEEKO` should normally also use `AC_SYS_LARGEFILE` to ensure that `off_t` can represent all supported file sizes.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] The Gnulib module `fseeko` invokes `AC_FUNC_FSEEKO` and also contains workarounds for other portability problems of `fseeko`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Perform all the checks performed by `AC_TYPE_GETGROUPS` (see AC_TYPE_GETGROUPS).
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Then, if the `getgroups` function is available and known to work correctly, define `HAVE_GETGROUPS`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Set the output variable `GETGROUPS_LIB` to any libraries needed to get that function.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] This macro relies on a list of systems with known, serious bugs in `getgroups`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If this list mis-identifies your system’s `getgroups` as buggy, or as not buggy, you can override it by setting the cache variable `ac_cv_func_getgroups_works` in a config.site file (see Setting Site Defaults).
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Please also report the error to the Autoconf Bugs mailing list.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] The Gnulib module `getgroups` provides workarounds for additional, less severe portability problems with this function.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Check how to get the system load averages.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] To perform its tests properly, this macro needs the file getloadavg.c; therefore, be sure to set the `AC_LIBOBJ` replacement directory properly (see Generic Function Checks, `AC_CONFIG_LIBOBJ_DIR`).
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If the system has the `getloadavg` function, define `HAVE_GETLOADAVG`, and set `GETLOADAVG_LIBS` to any libraries necessary to get that function.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Define `SVR4`, `DGUX`, `UMAX`, or `UMAX4_3` if on those systems.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If nlist.h is found, define `HAVE_NLIST_H`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If ‘struct nlist’ has an ‘n_un.n_name’ member, define `HAVE_STRUCT_NLIST_N_UN_N_NAME`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] The obsolete symbol `NLIST_NAME_UNION` is still defined, but do not depend upon it.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Programs may need to be installed set-group-ID (or set-user-ID) for `getloadavg` to work.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] In this case, define `GETLOADAVG_PRIVILEGED`, set the output variable `NEED_SETGID` to ‘true’ (and otherwise to ‘false’), and set `KMEM_GROUP` to the name of the group that should own the installed program.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] The `AC_FUNC_GETLOADAVG` macro is obsolescent.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] New programs should use Gnulib’s `getloadavg` module.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Check for `getmntent` in the standard C library, and then in the sun, seq, and gen libraries.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Then, if `getmntent` is available, define `HAVE_GETMNTENT` and set `ac_cv_func_getmntent` to `yes`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Otherwise set `ac_cv_func_getmntent` to `no`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] The result of this macro can be overridden by setting the cache variable `ac_cv_search_getmntent`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] The `AC_FUNC_GETMNTENT` macro is obsolescent.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] New programs should use Gnulib’s `mountlist` module.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Define `GETPGRP_VOID` if it is an error to pass 0 to `getpgrp`; this is the POSIX behavior.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] On older BSD systems, you must pass 0 to `getpgrp`, as it takes an argument and behaves like POSIX’s `getpgid`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] This macro does not check whether `getpgrp` exists at all; if you need to work in that situation, first call `AC_CHECK_FUNC` for `getpgrp`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] The result of this macro is cached in the `ac_cv_func_getpgrp_void` variable.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] This macro is obsolescent, as current systems have a `getpgrp` whose signature conforms to POSIX.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If link is a symbolic link, then `lstat` should treat link/ the same as link/..
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] However, many older `lstat` implementations incorrectly ignore trailing slashes.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] It is safe to assume that if `lstat` incorrectly ignores trailing slashes, then other symbolic-link-aware functions like `unlink` also incorrectly ignore trailing slashes.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If `lstat` behaves properly, define `LSTAT_FOLLOWS_SLASHED_SYMLINK`, otherwise require an `AC_LIBOBJ` replacement of `lstat`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] The result of this macro is cached in the `ac_cv_func_lstat_dereferences_slashed_symlink` variable.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] The `AC_FUNC_LSTAT_FOLLOWS_SLASHED_SYMLINK` macro is obsolescent.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] New programs should use Gnulib’s `lstat` module.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If the `malloc` function is compatible with the GNU C library `malloc` (i.e., ‘malloc (0)’ returns a valid pointer), define `HAVE_MALLOC` to 1.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Otherwise define `HAVE_MALLOC` to 0, ask for an `AC_LIBOBJ` replacement for ‘malloc’, and define `malloc` to `rpl_malloc` so that the native `malloc` is not used in the main project.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] The result of this macro is cached in the `ac_cv_func_malloc_0_nonnull` variable.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] The result might contain spaces, e.g., `guessing yes`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If you don’t want to maintain a `malloc.c` file in your package manually, you can instead use the Gnulib module `malloc-gnu`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Define `HAVE_MBRTOWC` to 1 if the function `mbrtowc` and the type `mbstate_t` are properly declared.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] The result of this macro is cached in the `ac_cv_func_mbrtowc` variable.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] The Gnulib module `mbrtowc` not only ensures that the function is declared, but also works around other portability problems of this function.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If the `memcmp` function is not available or does not work, require an `AC_LIBOBJ` replacement for ‘memcmp’.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] The result of this macro is cached in the `ac_cv_func_memcmp_working` variable.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] This macro is obsolescent, as current systems have a working `memcmp`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If the `mktime` function is not available, or does not work correctly, require an `AC_LIBOBJ` replacement for ‘mktime’.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] For the purposes of this test, `mktime` should conform to the POSIX standard and should be the inverse of `localtime`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] The result of this macro is cached in the `ac_cv_func_working_mktime` variable.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] The `AC_FUNC_MKTIME` macro is obsolescent.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] New programs should use Gnulib’s `mktime` module.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If the `mmap` function exists and works correctly, define `HAVE_MMAP`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] This checks only private fixed mapping of already-mapped memory.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] The result of this macro is cached in the `ac_cv_func_mmap_fixed_mapped` variable.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Note: This macro asks for more than what an average program needs from `mmap`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] In particular, the use of `MAP_FIXED` fails on HP-UX 11, whereas `mmap` otherwise works fine on this platform.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If the obstacks are found, define `HAVE_OBSTACK`, else require an `AC_LIBOBJ` replacement for ‘obstack’.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] The result of this macro is cached in the `ac_cv_func_obstack` variable.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] The `AC_FUNC_OBSTACK` macro is obsolescent.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] New programs should use Gnulib’s `obstack` module.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If a successful call to ‘realloc (NULL, 0)’ returns a non-null pointer, define `HAVE_REALLOC` to 1.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Otherwise define `HAVE_REALLOC` to 0, ask for an `AC_LIBOBJ` replacement for ‘realloc’, and define `realloc` to `rpl_realloc` so that the native `realloc` is not used in the main project.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] The result of this macro is cached in the `ac_cv_func_realloc_0_nonnull` variable.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] This macro does not check compatibility with glibc `realloc (*p*, 0)` when *p* is non-null, as glibc 1–2.1 behaves differently from glibc 2.1.1–2.40 (at least), and the C standard says behavior is undefined.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Determines the correct type to be passed for each of the `select` function’s arguments, and defines those types in `SELECT_TYPE_ARG1`, `SELECT_TYPE_ARG234`, and `SELECT_TYPE_ARG5` respectively.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] `SELECT_TYPE_ARG1` defaults to ‘int’, `SELECT_TYPE_ARG234` defaults to ‘int *’, and `SELECT_TYPE_ARG5` defaults to ‘struct timeval *’.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] This macro is obsolescent, as current systems have a `select` whose signature conforms to POSIX.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If `setpgrp` takes no argument (the POSIX version), define `SETPGRP_VOID`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Otherwise, it is the BSD version, which takes two process IDs as arguments.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] This macro does not check whether `setpgrp` exists at all; if you need to work in that situation, first call `AC_CHECK_FUNC` for `setpgrp`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] This macro also does not check for the Solaris variant of `setpgrp`, which returns a `pid_t` instead of an `int`; portable code should only use the return value by comparing it against `-1` to check for errors.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] The result of this macro is cached in the `ac_cv_func_setpgrp_void` variable.
