[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] These macros are used to find functions not covered by the “particular” test macros.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If the functions might be in libraries other than the default C library, first call `AC_CHECK_LIB` for those libraries.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If you need to check the behavior of a function as well as find out whether it is present, you have to write your own test for it (see Writing Tests).
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If C function *function* is available, run shell commands *action-if-found*, otherwise *action-if-not-found*.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If you just want to define a symbol if the function is available, consider using `AC_CHECK_FUNCS` instead.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] This macro checks for functions with C linkage even when `AC_LANG(C++)` has been called, since C is more standardized than C++.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] This macro caches its result in the `ac_cv_func_*function*` variable.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] For each *function* enumerated in the blank-or-newline-separated argument list, define `HAVE_*function*` (in all capitals) if it is available.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If *action-if-found* is given, it is additional shell code to execute when one of the functions is found.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] You can give it a value of ‘break’ to break out of the loop on the first match.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If *action-if-not-found* is given, it is executed when one of the functions is not found.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Results are cached for each *function* as in `AC_CHECK_FUNC`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] This is a once-only variant of `AC_CHECK_FUNCS`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] It generates the checking code at most once, so that `configure` is smaller and faster; but the checks cannot be conditionalized and are always done once, early during the `configure` run.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Autoconf follows a philosophy that was formed over the years by those who have struggled for portability: isolate the portability issues in specific files, and then program as if you were in a POSIX environment.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Some functions may be missing or unfixable, and your package must be ready to replace them.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Suitable replacements for many such problem functions are available from Gnulib (see Gnulib).
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Specify that ‘*function*.c’ must be included in the executables to replace a missing or broken implementation of *function*.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Technically, it adds ‘*function*.$ac_objext’ to the output variable `LIBOBJS` if it is not already in, and calls `AC_LIBSOURCE` for ‘*function*.c’.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] You should not directly change `LIBOBJS`, since this is not traceable.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Specify that *file* might be needed to compile the project.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If you need to know what files might be needed by a configure.ac, you should trace `AC_LIBSOURCE`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] This macro is called automatically from `AC_LIBOBJ`, but you must call it explicitly if you pass a shell variable to `AC_LIBOBJ`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] In that case, since shell variables cannot be traced statically, you must pass to `AC_LIBSOURCE` any possible files that the shell variable might cause `AC_LIBOBJ` to need.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] There is usually a way to avoid this, however, and you are encouraged to simply call `AC_LIBOBJ` with literal arguments.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Note that this macro replaces the obsolete `AC_LIBOBJ_DECL`, with slightly different semantics: the old macro took the function name, e.g., `foo`, as its argument rather than the file name.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Like `AC_LIBSOURCE`, but accepts one or more *files* in a comma-separated M4 list.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Specify that `AC_LIBOBJ` replacement files are to be found in *directory*, a name relative to the top level of the source tree.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] The replacement directory defaults to ., the top level directory, and the most typical value is lib, corresponding to ‘AC_CONFIG_LIBOBJ_DIR([lib])’.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] It is common to merely check for the existence of a function, and ask for its `AC_LIBOBJ` replacement if missing.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] The following macro is a convenient shorthand.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Like `AC_CHECK_FUNCS`, but uses ‘AC_LIBOBJ(*function*)’ as *action-if-not-found*.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] You can declare your replacement function by enclosing the prototype in ‘#ifndef HAVE_*function*’.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If the system has the function, it probably declares it in a header file you should be including, so you shouldn’t redeclare it lest your declaration conflict.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] The following macros check for the presence of certain C header files.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If there is no macro specifically defined to check for a header file you need, and you don’t need to check for any special properties of it, then you can use one of the general header-file check macros.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] This section documents some collected knowledge about common headers, and the problems they cause.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] A much more complete list is maintained by the Gnulib project (see Gnulib), covering POSIX Headers in *Gnulib* and Glibc Headers in *Gnulib*.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] When we say that a header “may require” some set of other headers, we mean that it may be necessary for you to manually include those other headers first, or the contents of the header under test will fail to compile.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] When checking for these headers, you must provide the potentially-required headers in the *includes* argument to `AC_CHECK_HEADER` or `AC_CHECK_HEADERS`, or the check will fail spuriously.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] `AC_INCLUDES_DEFAULT` (see Default Includes) arranges to include a number of common requirements and should normally come first in your *includes*.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Note that the example mixes single quoting (for`AC_INCLUDES_DEFAULT`, so that it gets expanded) and double quoting (to ensure that each preprocessor `#` gets treated as a literal string rather than a comment).
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] In C99 and later, limits.h defines `LLONG_MIN`, `LLONG_MAX`, and `ULLONG_MAX`, but many almost-C99 environments (e.g., default GCC 4.0.2 + glibc 2.4) do not define them.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] This header file is obsolete; use string.h instead.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] On some systems, this is the only header that declares `strcasecmp`, `strncasecmp`, and `ffs`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] This header may or may not include string.h for you.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] However, on all recent systems it is safe to include both string.h and strings.h, in either order, in the same source file.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] C99 specifies that inttypes.h includes stdint.h, so there’s no need to include stdint.h separately in a standard environment.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] However, some implementations have stdint.h but not inttypes.h (e.g.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Therefore, it is necessary to check for each and include each only if available.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] This header may require linux/types.h and/or sys/socket.h.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] This header may require sys/types.h and/or sys/socket.h.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] This header may require some combination of sys/types.h, sys/socket.h, netinet/in.h, and net/if.h.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Using XFree86, this header requires X11/Xlib.h, which is probably so required that you might not even consider looking for it.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] These macros check for particular system header files—whether they exist, and in some cases whether they declare certain symbols.
