[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Check whether to enable assertions in the style of assert.h.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Assertions are enabled by default, but the user can override this by invoking `configure` with the --disable-assert option.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Using the above declarations, the program would declare variables to be of type `struct dirent`, not `struct direct`, and would access the length of a directory entry name by passing a pointer to a `struct dirent` to the `NAMLEN` macro.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] This macro also checks for the obsolete dir and x libraries.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] This macro is obsolescent, as all current systems with directory libraries have `<dirent.h>`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Also see `AC_STRUCT_DIRENT_D_INO` and `AC_STRUCT_DIRENT_D_TYPE` (see Particular Structure Checks).
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Detect the headers required to use `makedev`, `major`, and `minor`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] These functions may be defined by sys/mkdev.h, `sys/sysmacros.h`, or sys/types.h.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] `AC_HEADER_MAJOR` defines `MAJOR_IN_MKDEV` if they are in sys/mkdev.h, or `MAJOR_IN_SYSMACROS` if they are in sys/sysmacros.h.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If neither macro is defined, they are either in sys/types.h or unavailable.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Note: Configure scripts built with Autoconf 2.69 or earlier will not detect a problem if sys/types.h contains definitions of `major`, `minor`, and/or `makedev` that trigger compiler warnings upon use.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] This is known to occur with GNU libc 2.25, where those definitions are being deprecated to reduce namespace pollution.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If it is not practical to use Autoconf 2.70 to regenerate the configure script of affected software, you can work around the problem by setting ‘ac_cv_header_sys_types_h_makedev=no’, as an argument to `configure` or as part of a config.site site default file (see Setting Site Defaults).
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Checks for header resolv.h, checking for prerequisites first.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If the macros `S_ISDIR`, `S_ISREG`, etc. defined in sys/stat.h do not work properly (returning false positives), define `STAT_MACROS_BROKEN`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] This is the case on Tektronix UTekV, Amdahl UTS and Motorola System V/88.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] This macro is obsolescent, as no current systems have the bug.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If stdbool.h exists and conforms to C99 or later, define `HAVE_STDBOOL_H` to 1; if the type `_Bool` is defined, define `HAVE__BOOL` to 1.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Nowadays programs that need `bool`, `true` and `false` can include stdbool.h unconditionally, without using `AC_HEADER_STDBOOL`, and if such a program needs to be portable only to C23 or later it need not even include stdbool.h.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] This macro caches its result in the `ac_cv_header_stdbool_h` variable.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] This macro differs from `AC_CHECK_HEADER_STDBOOL` only in that it defines `HAVE_STDBOOL_H` whereas `AC_CHECK_HEADER_STDBOOL` does not.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Its sole effect is to make sure that all the headers that are included by `AC_INCLUDES_DEFAULT` (see Default Includes), but not part of C89, have been checked for.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] All hosted environments that are still of interest for portable code provide all of the headers specified in C89 (as amended in 1995).
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If sys/wait.h exists and is compatible with POSIX, define `HAVE_SYS_WAIT_H`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Incompatibility can occur if sys/wait.h does not exist, or if it uses the old BSD `union wait` instead of `int` to store a status value.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If sys/wait.h is not POSIX compatible, then instead of including it, define the POSIX macros with their usual interpretations.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] This macro caches its result in the `ac_cv_header_sys_wait_h` variable.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] This macro is obsolescent, as current systems are compatible with POSIX.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] `_POSIX_VERSION` is defined when unistd.h is included on POSIX systems.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If there is no unistd.h, it is definitely not a POSIX system.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] However, some non-POSIX systems do have unistd.h.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If the use of `TIOCGWINSZ` requires <sys/ioctl.h>, then define `GWINSZ_IN_SYS_IOCTL`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Otherwise `TIOCGWINSZ` can be found in <termios.h>.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] These macros are used to find system header files not covered by the “particular” test macros.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If you need to check the contents of a header as well as find out whether it is present, you have to write your own test for it (see Writing Tests).
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If the system header file *header-file* is compilable, execute shell commands *action-if-found*, otherwise execute *action-if-not-found*.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If you just want to define a symbol if the header file is available, consider using `AC_CHECK_HEADERS` instead.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] This macro used to check only for the *presence* of a header, not whether its contents were acceptable to the compiler.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Some older `configure` scripts rely on this behavior, so it is still available by specifying ‘-’ as *includes*.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] This mechanism is deprecated as of Autoconf 2.70; situations where a preprocessor-only check is required should use `AC_PREPROC_IFELSE`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] This macro caches its result in the `ac_cv_header_*header-file*` variable, with characters not suitable for a variable name mapped to underscores.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] For each given system header file *header-file* in the blank-separated argument list that exists, define `HAVE_*header-file*` (in all capitals).
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If *action-if-found* is given, it is additional shell code to execute when one of the header files is found.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If *action-if-not-found* is given, it is executed when one of the header files is not found.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If you do not need the full power of `AC_CHECK_HEADERS`, this variant generates smaller, faster `configure` files.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] All headers passed to `AC_CHECK_HEADERS_ONCE` are checked for in one pass, early during the `configure` run.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] The checks cannot be conditionalized, you cannot specify an *action-if-found* or *action-if-not-found*, and `AC_INCLUDES_DEFAULT` is always used for the prerequisites.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] In previous versions of Autoconf, these macros merely checked whether the header was accepted by the preprocessor.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] This was changed because the old test was inappropriate for typical uses.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Headers are typically used to compile, not merely to preprocess, and the old behavior sometimes accepted headers that clashed at compile-time (see Header Present But Cannot Be Compiled).
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If for some reason it is inappropriate to check whether a header is compilable, you should use `AC_PREPROC_IFELSE` (see Running the Preprocessor) instead of these macros.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Requiring each header to compile improves the robustness of the test, but it also requires you to make sure that the *includes* are correct.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Most system headers nowadays make sure to `#include` whatever they require, or else have their dependencies satisfied by `AC_INCLUDES_DEFAULT` (see Default Includes), but see Portability of Headers, for known exceptions.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] The following macros check for the declaration of variables and functions.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If there is no macro specifically defined to check for a symbol you need, then you can use the general macros (see Generic Declaration Checks) or, for more complex tests, you may use `AC_COMPILE_IFELSE` (see Running the Compiler).
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] There are no specific macros for declarations.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] These macros are used to find declarations not covered by the “particular” test macros.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If *symbol* (a function, variable, or constant) is not declared in *includes* and a declaration is needed, run the shell commands *action-if-not-found*, otherwise *action-if-found*.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] *includes* is a series of include directives, defaulting to `AC_INCLUDES_DEFAULT` (see Default Includes), which are used prior to the declaration under test.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] This macro actually tests whether *symbol* is defined as a macro or can be used as an r-value, not whether it is really declared, because it is much safer to avoid introducing extra declarations when they are not needed.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] This macro caches its result in the `ac_cv_have_decl_*symbol*` variable, with characters not suitable for a variable name mapped to underscores.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] For each of the *symbols* (*comma*-separated list with optional function argument types for C++ overloads), define `HAVE_DECL_*symbol*` (in all capitals) to ‘1’ if *symbol* is declared, otherwise to ‘0’.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If *action-if-not-found* is given, it is additional shell code to execute when one of the function declarations is needed, otherwise *action-if-found* is executed.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Unlike the other ‘AC_CHECK_*S’ macros, when a *symbol* is not declared, `HAVE_DECL_*symbol*` is defined to ‘0’ instead of leaving `HAVE_DECL_*symbol*` undeclared.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] You fall into the second category only in extreme situations: either your files may be used without being configured, or they are used during the configuration.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] In most cases the traditional approach is enough.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] This macro caches its results in `ac_cv_have_decl_*symbol*` variables, with characters not suitable for a variable name mapped to underscores.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] For each of the *symbols* (*comma*-separated list), define `HAVE_DECL_*symbol*` (in all capitals) to ‘1’ if *symbol* is declared in the default include files, otherwise to ‘0’.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] This is a once-only variant of `AC_CHECK_DECLS`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] The following macros check for the presence of certain members in C structures.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If there is no macro specifically defined to check for a member you need, then you can use the general structure-member macros (see Generic Structure Checks) or, for more complex tests, you may use `AC_COMPILE_IFELSE` (see Running the Compiler).
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] The following macros check for certain structures or structure members.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Perform all the actions of `AC_HEADER_DIRENT` (see Particular Header Checks).
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Then, if `struct dirent` contains a `d_ino` member, define `HAVE_STRUCT_DIRENT_D_INO`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] `HAVE_STRUCT_DIRENT_D_INO` indicates only the presence of `d_ino`, not whether its contents are always reliable.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Traditionally, a zero `d_ino` indicated a deleted directory entry, though current systems hide this detail from the user and never return zero `d_ino` values.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Many current systems report an incorrect `d_ino` for a directory entry that is a mount point.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Then, if `struct dirent` contains a `d_type` member, define `HAVE_STRUCT_DIRENT_D_TYPE`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If `struct stat` contains an `st_blocks` member, define `HAVE_STRUCT_STAT_ST_BLOCKS`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] Otherwise, require an `AC_LIBOBJ` replacement of ‘fileblocks’.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] The former name, `HAVE_ST_BLOCKS` is to be avoided, as its support will cease in the future.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] This macro caches its result in the `ac_cv_member_struct_stat_st_blocks` variable.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p04] If time.h does not define `struct tm`, define `TM_IN_SYS_TIME`, which means that including sys/time.h had better define `struct tm`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p05] This macro is obsolescent, as time.h defines `struct tm` in current systems.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p05] Figure out how to get the current timezone.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p05] If `struct tm` has a `tm_zone` member, define `HAVE_STRUCT_TM_TM_ZONE` (and the obsoleted `HAVE_TM_ZONE`).
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p05] Otherwise, if the external array `tzname` is found, define `HAVE_TZNAME`; if it is declared, define `HAVE_DECL_TZNAME`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p05] These macros are used to find structure members not covered by the “particular” test macros.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p05] Check whether *member* is a member of the aggregate *aggregate*.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p05] If no *includes* are specified, the default includes are used (see Default Includes).
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p05] This macro caches its result in the `ac_cv_member_*aggregate*_*member*` variable, with characters not suitable for a variable name mapped to underscores.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p05] Check for the existence of each ‘*aggregate*.*member*’ of *members* using the previous macro.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p05] When *member* belongs to *aggregate*, define `HAVE_*aggregate*_*member*` (in all capitals, with spaces and dots replaced by underscores).
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p05] If *action-if-found* is given, it is executed for each of the found members.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p05] If *action-if-not-found* is given, it is executed for each of the members that could not be found.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p05] The following macros check for C types, either builtin or typedefs.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p05] If there is no macro specifically defined to check for a type you need, and you don’t need to check for any special properties of it, then you can use a general type-check macro.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p05] These macros check for particular C types in sys/types.h, stdlib.h, stdint.h, inttypes.h and others, if they exist.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p05] The Gnulib `stdint` module is an alternate way to define many of these symbols; it is useful if you prefer your code to assume a C99-or-better environment.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p05] Define `GETGROUPS_T` to be whichever of `gid_t` or `int` is the base type of the array argument to `getgroups`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p05] This macro caches the base type in the `ac_cv_type_getgroups` variable.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p05] If stdint.h or inttypes.h does not define the type `int8_t`, define `int8_t` to a signed integer type that is exactly 8 bits wide and that uses two’s complement representation, if such a type exists.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p05] This macro caches the type in the `ac_cv_c_int8_t` variable.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p05] This is like `AC_TYPE_INT8_T`, except for 16-bit integers.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p05] This is like `AC_TYPE_INT8_T`, except for 32-bit integers.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p05] This is like `AC_TYPE_INT8_T`, except for 64-bit integers.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p05] If stdint.h or inttypes.h defines the type `intmax_t`, define `HAVE_INTMAX_T`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p05] Otherwise, define `intmax_t` to the widest signed integer type.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p05] If stdint.h or inttypes.h defines the type `intptr_t`, define `HAVE_INTPTR_T`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p05] Otherwise, define `intptr_t` to a signed integer type wide enough to hold a pointer, if such a type exists.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p05] If the C compiler supports a working `long double` type, define `HAVE_LONG_DOUBLE`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p05] The `long double` type might have the same range and precision as `double`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p05] This macro caches its result in the `ac_cv_type_long_double` variable.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p05] This macro is obsolescent, as current C compilers support `long double`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p05] If the C compiler supports a working `long double` type with more range or precision than the `double` type, define `HAVE_LONG_DOUBLE_WIDER`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p05] This macro caches its result in the `ac_cv_type_long_double_wider` variable.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p05] If the C compiler supports a working `long long int` type, define `HAVE_LONG_LONG_INT`.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p05] However, this test does not test `long long int` values in preprocessor `#if` expressions, because too many compilers mishandle such expressions.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p05] This macro caches its result in the `ac_cv_type_long_long_int` variable.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p05] Define `HAVE_MBSTATE_T` if `<wchar.h>` declares the `mbstate_t` type.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p05] Also, define `mbstate_t` to be a type if `<wchar.h>` does not declare it.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p05] This macro caches its result in the `ac_cv_type_mbstate_t` variable.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p05] Define `mode_t` to a suitable type, if standard headers do not define it.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p05] This macro caches its result in the `ac_cv_type_mode_t` variable.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p05] Define `off_t` to a suitable type, if standard headers do not define it.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p05] This macro caches its result in the `ac_cv_type_off_t` variable.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p05] Define `pid_t` to a suitable type, if standard headers do not define it.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p05] This macro caches its result in the `ac_cv_type_pid_t` variable.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p05] Define `size_t` to a suitable type, if standard headers do not define it.
[src:gnu-autotools/autoconf-p05] This macro caches its result in the `ac_cv_type_size_t` variable.
